Bug: GCC 14+ made -Wimplicit-function-declaration, -Wimplicit-int, and
-Wincompatible-pointer-types errors by default when compiling C (they
used to be warnings). That newly trips up pre-C99-strict vendored C
code (cairo, pixman, and likely others) which predates that default
and was never explicitly -Werror'd for these historically. Keep them
as non-fatal warnings so this old C code still builds against modern
toolchains, matching how it always behaved until the GCC default changed.
Index: configure.in
--- a/configure.in	Thu Jan 08 23:22:45 2015 -0500
+++ b/configure.in	Sun Jul 12 05:06:58 2026 +0800
@@ -1459,6 +1459,17 @@
     _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Werror=trigraphs"
     _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Werror=unknown-pragmas"
 
+    # GCC 14+ made -Wimplicit-function-declaration, -Wimplicit-int, and
+    # -Wincompatible-pointer-types errors by default for C (previously
+    # just warnings). This trips up pre-C99-strict vendored C code (e.g.
+    # cairo, pixman) that predates that default and was never -Werror'd
+    # for these historically. Keep them as (non-fatal) warnings here so
+    # this old code still builds against modern toolchains.
+    _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Wno-error=implicit-function-declaration"
+    _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Wno-error=implicit-int"
+    _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Wno-error=incompatible-pointer-types"
+    _WARNINGS_CFLAGS="${_WARNINGS_CFLAGS} -Wno-error=int-conversion"
+
     # Turn off the following warnings that -Wall turns on:
     # -Wno-unused - lots of violations in third-party code
     #
